## AI Agent Workflow

### Codex CLI Role

Codex CLI loads this file natively (no `@import` needed). Defaults to `gpt-5` as of 2026. Good fit: precise diff-style edits, deterministic code transformations, well-specified sub-tasks where ~5 prompt constraints fully define the work.

### Antigravity CLI Role

Antigravity CLI (`agy`) loads this file natively (no `@import` needed, same as Codex). Replaces Gemini CLI per Google's 2026-05-19 announcement; Antigravity is built in Go, free-tier quota refreshes every 5h. Good fit: long-context reads (large diffs / file scans), Google Workspace via `gws` CLI, multimodal (image / PDF) input, well-specified sub-tasks with clear acceptance tests.

### Gemini CLI Role (legacy — sunsets 2026-06-18)

Gemini CLI loads this file via `@./AGENTS.md` import in `GEMINI.md`. Free tier deprecates 2026-06-18 per [Google announcement](https://developers.googleblog.com/an-important-update-transitioning-gemini-cli-to-antigravity-cli/) — migrate to Antigravity CLI before the deadline. Until then, same role-fit as Antigravity. Gemini does NOT follow symlinks at the `GEMINI.md` path (issue #11547, closed `not_planned` 2025-11-21) — keep `GEMINI.md` as a real file, not a symlink.

### Branch & Push Rules (applies to all delegated CLIs)

PR flow, not direct push to `main`:

1. Agent works on a feature branch named `<cli>/<task-slug>` (e.g. `codex/cleanup-imports`, `agy/redesign-empty-state`).
2. Before committing, agent runs and confirms green: typecheck + lint commands defined in "Build, Test, and Development Commands" below. For DB-touching work, also run any DB verification command.
3. Commit using conventional style (`feat(scope): ...`, `fix(scope): ...`, etc.) with `Co-Authored-By: <CLI> <noreply@<vendor>.com>` trailer (`<noreply@openai.com>` for Codex, `<noreply@google.com>` for Antigravity CLI, `<noreply@google.com>` for Gemini CLI until sunset).
4. Push the branch to origin and open a PR against `main`. Title = the conventional commit title. Body = what changed, what was tested, what the spec said.
5. Do **NOT** self-merge. Wait for human review (or Claude orchestrator in multi-CLI setup).
6. **Do NOT deploy from a feature branch.** Deploys happen post-merge from `main`, by the user or by Claude as orchestrator. Branch-deploy causes `main` ↔ prod desync (any later main-deploy reverts the agent's work).

### Multi-CLI Parallel Workflow

When running Codex and Antigravity (or any 2+ CLIs / instances) concurrently on the same repo, give each its own worktree to avoid shared-state conflicts:

```bash
# Standard layout — name worktrees by FUNCTION, not by model.
# This survives multi-instance scenarios (e.g. 2 Antigravity instances on different tasks):
git worktree add ../<project>-<function-slug> <cli>/<task-branch>
# Examples:
git worktree add ../<project>-empty-states  agy/redesign-empty-state
git worktree add ../<project>-lint-fixes    codex/cleanup-imports
git worktree add ../<project>-feature-x-ui  agy/feature-x-ui
git worktree add ../<project>-feature-x-api agy/feature-x-api  # second agy instance, distinct dir
```

Branch name still encodes the CLI (`<cli>/<task-slug>` per Branch & Push Rules), so the worktree directory shows *what* is being worked on while the branch tells *who*.

Then launch each CLI in its own directory. The main worktree (`<project>/`) stays reserved for Claude (orchestration, review, merge, post-merge deploy).

**Why function-based naming:** When a user wants to run 2 Antigravity instances (or 2 Codex instances) on different tasks, model-based naming (`-agy` / `-agy-2`) is ambiguous; function-based naming (`-feature-x-ui` / `-feature-x-api`) makes the parent directory listing self-documenting.

**Why worktrees at all:** When CLIs share a single worktree, one CLI switching branches under the other causes "stale `M file`" panic and stalls execution. Worktrees share git history but each has its own working tree state.

**Cleanup after merge:** `git worktree remove ../<project>-<function-slug>` once the PR is merged. Don't accumulate stale worktrees.

Single-agent rounds (only one CLI at a time) don't need worktree isolation — just use the main worktree.

**Orchestration brief rule (Claude side):** When writing a delegation brief for Codex, Antigravity, or any delegated CLI, the brief's ship section ends at "open PR, wait for review". Do NOT include a deploy command in the brief — let AGENTS.md's "agents don't deploy" rule (above) be canonical. Brief-level deploy instructions risk causing the agent to deploy from its feature branch, creating a branch→prod desync window.

**Anti-pattern guard for delegated CLIs:** Do NOT remove a worktree you were assigned to, do NOT switch the main worktree's branch, and do NOT skip opening a PR even if the local branch is in an unexpected state. Surface the blocker back to Claude / the user instead of self-recovering destructively. (Observed incident logged in anchor session 77 / 2026-05-27.)

**Dispatch pattern (Claude side, optional but recommended):** To reduce copy-paste during multi-CLI rounds, Claude writes each delegation brief to a file (suggested path: `<briefs-dir>/<cli>-current.md`, e.g. `_bmad-output/briefs/codex-current.md`). User dispatches with one line: "read that path and follow it". When the agent finishes, user reports only the branch name (e.g. "done, branch `codex/cleanup-imports`") — Claude inspects via `gh pr view` / `git diff origin/<branch>` rather than expecting the agent's chat transcript.

## Tool Preference: CLI over MCP

When a service offers both a CLI and an MCP server, prefer the CLI. Reasons:

- **Token efficiency.** Benchmarks show ~17x fewer tokens per task for CLI vs MCP (Firecrawl / Arize, 2025).
- **Cross-agent auth.** CLI auth lives in `~/.config/<tool>/` and is shared across Claude / Codex / Antigravity / Gemini. MCP OAuth is per-agent.
- **Reliability.** CLI flow is one process call; MCP adds a server hop.

**Preferred CLIs** (install status defaults to `⏳ not installed`; bootstrap user should run `command -v <tool>` per their machine and update to `✓ installed` where applicable):

| Service | Preferred CLI | Install status | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| GitHub | `gh` | ⏳ not installed | Widely installed, mature. |
| Google Workspace (Gmail / Calendar / Drive) | `gws` | ⏳ not installed | Official Google CLI, pre-1.0 as of 2026-05. |
| Google Drive bulk ops | `rclone` | ⏳ not installed | Mature alternative to `gws` for large transfers. |
| Notion | `ntn` | ⏳ not installed | Official, young. |
| Browser scripted flows | Playwright CLI | ⏳ not installed | Mature; use Playwright Python for headless automation. |
| JIRA | `acli` | ⏳ not installed | Atlassian official, GA 2026. |

**Important for sub-agent prompts:** When delegating a task that requires a CLI tool, check this matrix's install status FIRST. For `⏳ not installed`, do one of: (a) ask the user to install before delegating, (b) fall back to the corresponding MCP if available, or (c) use a closer-fit alternative. Do NOT prompt sub-agents (Codex / Antigravity / Gemini) to invoke a tool listed as `⏳ not installed` — they will fail silently or hallucinate output.

### Stay on MCP (no viable CLI)

- **Canva** — no design content management CLI.
- **chrome-devtools** — interactive debug; the CLI surface is too thin.
- **context7** — library docs lookup; the MCP is the primary interface.

